I am a very fast typist, always have been since I learned how to type
in junior high school on a manual typewriter, without letters/numbers
on the keys.  LOL

My first job interview on an electric typewriter, I had MANY errors, me
being used to banging those manual keys pretty hard.  It was quite
depressing at the time.

If I had to take a test today where I had to take my hand off the
keyboard and use the mouse during the test, it would slow me down for
sure.

In today's transcription world with the shorthand macro programs, it
does help to accelerate one's speed.  I only use about 300-plus
"regular" words in my shorthand macro program, but I couldn't imagine
working without it. ;&gt;)

When I was younger, I went to take a transcription test at a medical
transcription company in my area.  When the test began, I realized
there was no auto-reverse feature on the transcriber machine.  What a
joke, like someone can type as fast as the person speaking.  I asked
the testing lady about it, and she did not know what an auto-reverse
feature was and looked at me like I was a Kling-on invading the
Starship Enterprise.  Again, I did horrible on this test for the job
interview and did not bother calling them back.  I knew I looked bad on
paper. :&gt;(

I think it is helpful to have some sort of typing speed if you're going
to be in this business.  In my world, we get paid by the page.
Beginners may bang out 5 to 10 pages an hour on relatively easy
content, but if it is a technical job, one requiring a lot of research,
then they would be lucky to earn minimum wage.  With my shorthand macro
program, I average 20 to 30 pages an hour for easy content.  When the
the foreign accents and poor quality audio recordings come into play,
only the veterans survive.  Nobody wants to touch these recordings with
a 10-foot pole, but sometimes you have to take the bad with the good.

In sum, typing speed is important in this racket, but it is not the
only necessary trait.  Attention for detail is just as important, IMHO,
like making an effort to get the words spelled right as opposed to
inserting [ph] and/or [inaudible] throughout a transcript.  When
getting paid by the page, some folks do not like going the extra mile
to look up stuff.

I am not so sure I would agree that SPEED is the only trait one needs
to be successful in the transcription world, but it sure does help.

The only time I had to get certified was for stenotype in the court
reporting arena.  About 30 years later, I am living proof that one does
not need to be certified and/or accredited to be a transcriptionist in
today's transcription world.

Oh, yeah, I almost forgot.  Being on time with the transcript is just
as important as being good.  If you're late, it doesn't matter one iota
how good the transcript is.  JMHO, FWIW!

Jennie the DOS Dinosaur who doesn't like the Mouse
Washington, D.C.

