"My big problem with the CMT test is the time limit.   I'm a
self-taught typist and just don't have the speed necessary so it would
be a waste of my time and money to even attempt it."

The CMT exam is not about speed.  They give you 5 hours to finish the
test, I think, which is PLENTY.  I think I finished it in a little
under 2 hours.  The test does a good job of measuring what you KNOW,
your fund of retained knowledge.  It also tests your critical thinking
skills.  The audio clips are short and not having a pedal is not really
a factor at all.

Certainly the exam is not perfect in that it does not measure things
like researching skills.  But the reality is that pretty much all
professional competency tests are built on this same model, whether
they're offered by AHIMA or any other professional association.
Prometric, the company who administers the exam, also administers
competency exams for many, many other entities, all using the same
basic model as the CMT/RMT exams.

The bottom line is that someone who has worked in multiple specialties
for a few years and has the knack for MT should be able to pass the CMT
exam.  It's not too easy and it's not too hard, in my opinion, although
it is challenging, no mistake about that.  But that's what tests are
supposed to be.

Jay
